mport sequence triggers a classic Python import cycle. I need to break it! My current line of thought is that `init_db.py` can import `Base` from `base_class` to allow `Base.metadata.create_all(bind=engine)` to create all tables. This mandates that all models be imported before `create_all` is called; otherwise, they are not registered in `Base.metadata`. I'm going to look at ways `init_db` imports to get around this.\n\n\n**Deferring Import Execution**\n\nI've got a promising lead on deferred execution. Moving the `Base` import inside the `init_db()` function in `init_db.py` seems to resolve the import-time cycle. This delays the `Base` import, bypassing the circular dependency during module loading. Now, I'm tracing the implications when importing the `User` model, specifically how this impacts module loading flow.\n\n\n**Confirming Import Order**\n\nI've just validated the import sequence, and it's remarkably clean. The models load sequentially without any hiccups. Importantly, `init_db` loads successfully because it imports `Base` only after everything else is fully initialized. The `Session` and `engine` import don't have cyclic dependencies and load. This structure is both robust and elegant.\n\n\n"}}
